text: hi everyone anime money tornado here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for review of the new black milk
record if there's a hell below black
milk detroit MC and producer he's been
at it for over a decade now and he is
dropping his sixth full-length album
right here a record i was kind of
surprised was coming out so fast given
that his last full-length album was out
just a year ago no poison no paradise
and of course i was looking forward to
this album because I enjoyed that album
the production on this record is grimy
it's low Phi it's jazzy it's funky there
are loads of textured synthesizers
peppered throughout these beats if
you're into people like J Dilla or mad
lib or Kareem brigands you're gonna
enjoy the beats on this record I still
had my minor reservations with black
milks rapping as I had on some of his
previous records but uh no poison no
paradise black milks lack of enthusiasm
and technical skill was made up for by
some of his most personal verses yet a
lot of songs on this record were coming
from a sort of dark introspective and
occasionally nostalgic place and maybe
there was a chance that this next record
of his would be even more hellish and
dark given that the title is if there's
a Hell below that's what I thought in
theory but in actuality this record
isn't really all that hellish no more
hellish than no poison no paradise there
are a few exceptions in the tracklist
here but for the most part the beats on
this new record come from roughly the
same place and milk's delivery is
roughly the same as well not that I
expect a whole ton of progression within
a year's time but there's such a lack of
progression on this record that Black
Milk openly revisits topics that he
talked about on his last album whether
that be some of his family or just
trying to survive and continue and stay
successful in hip-hop I guess all I can
say about this record is that Black Milk
is at what I suppose is a very
reflective point in his career and he
just feels
affordable rapping about what he knows
like on the song what it's worth which
is another visit to black milk's mental
hustle in the hip-hop industry reminding
himself of why he does what he does for
his fans for his fans
it's not that exciting but the
determination is admirable
then there's tracks like leave the bones
behind with blue and blues guest verse
isn't bad but this song is severely
under produced it's like just a loop
from a song used as a beat which I guess
there are fantastic songs that in the
past function off of that simplicity
that minimalism but it doesn't really
keep the track interesting here
especially since Black Milk isn't really
that electrifying of a rapper to begin
with the song every day was is another
nostalgic look into black milk's past
with him being in school kids banging on
desks making beats causing ruckus
dropouts failed rap dreams and another
similarly muddy vocal hook that feel a
little cloudy in the same way that the
vocals were kind of cloudy on black
notes last record then we get tracks on
here like scum with random acts which is
the trio that Black Milk has made music
with previously featuring Sean price and
guilty Simpson and this song has some
decent verses from guilty and Sean
though I do kind of cringe just a little
bit at that you rap dude do but on top
of that this song doesn't really feel
like one song but rather three different
songs because the beat changes up
significantly when guilty enters the
picture when Sean enters the picture and
it's like things shift so much that I
don't even feel like I'm listening to
the same track anymore and there are
other tracks here that feels similarly
disjointed or have like a little weird
instrumental interlude tacked on right
at the end of the track that doesn't
really add anything to the equation for
me the most fun and interesting track on
the entire record which is also maybe
the most unorthodox track for Black Milk
is Detroit's new dance show which has
this awesome beat that sounds like I
don't know the the the backing
instrumental to what would be a dance
music competition on like some
public-access television show where
people are just popping and locking in
breakdancing black milk has some alright
lyrics on this track but I have to admit
I don't really love the song for its
lyrics as much as I do it's instrumental
flavor and its groove there's also the
song story in her which when it begins
it kind of starts like an inconspicuous
old love old flame old crush story where
Black Milk is meeting up with someone
who at one time he had feelings for she
never really gave him the time of day
she was with other guys and meeting up
with her later in life she is interested
now they get together and then there is
a super crazy twist ending that I did
not expect at all
so Black Milk does have a few tricks up
his sleeve in the tracklisting here but
much of what he delivers on this record
is relatively average for him at this
point in his career I'm getting a lot of
the same ideas and expressions and
themes that I did on his last LP but for
reasons of either production or lyric
writing or lack of hook or something
like that the material is just a little
less compelling Black Milk really is
treading some water on this record and
he's delivered some less interesting
instrumentals and there are some tracks
here especially with the last two songs
and the track listing that feel more
like they are motifs ideas for songs
than they are fully realized and fleshed
out songs I did come away liking this
album for the most part but you know
nowhere near loving it or amazed or
surprised I'm feeling a light too decent
